>>114232925
Conducting is probably the single hardest job in the orchestra. Each instrumentalists only needs to know their part for any given piece. The conductor needs to know EVERY part, and he needs to know them inside and out. He uses one hand to provide a visual metronome to keep the players on time, and uses the other hand to simultaneously give directions to different sections about their expression (louder, quieter, more vibrato, etc.). Ultimately, the conductor is the one bringing all the different instrumentalists together and unifying their sound for the audience. It might look silly but it's a tough, tough job.

i didn't have lessons but i was absolutely consumed by the instrument for most of that time, i mean i had to practice in the shed during winter because of my family and i'd stay out there until 3-4am every day, something in me just hated the idea of not learning the instrument. i was 17 when i started and i was afraid that i started too late, which i probably did, but i'm finally getting to a point where i'm more and more satisfied with my tone production.

it's easy to draw the bow over the string but in the beginning you don't really have the muscles needed to really control the bow, you're just sort of dragging it, and it will be hard to have nice long bow strokes. the thing about playing in tune is that even if it's an open string you can still be out of tune because the bow can alter the pitch, so in the beginning, when you have inconsistent bow speed, you end up with a sound that goes up and down and sounds awful. i'm not saying you can't do it but i definitely couldn't for at least the first 2-3 years. that's how long it took me to get a consistent tone out of my violin.

>>114249504
Generally a great melodic facility is associated with the competence for the vocal idiom, and Mozart was among the greatest in this regard. This competence for the long, lyrical line can be found in his instrumental as well as vocal works, and can be contrasted with a composer like Beethoven who preferred to use smaller motivic cells. By simple, clear, and effortless, I mean more than one application of a special facility, but it includes things like the sense of proportion—the balance between unpredictable developments and the resolution which lands just so—and the ability to make even complex gestures like the fugato in Symphony No. 41 or the finale of Figaro Act II sound so seamless that you could miss how meticulous it is. Its aesthetic character differs from much of Romantic music in this way; it is not music that 'sweats', so to speak.
>what emotions do they bring
This is not a question that can be answered since music by nature can stimulate different emotions. Mozart does not stimulate just one feeling.

You asked me what I love in Mozart's music, and these are the particular musical qualities that stimulate that love—why I might love Mozart's music over another composer's. The emotions I feel are a secondary effect of music, and not strictly relevant except as a matter of intensity. It would not answer your question besides: for example, if I were to say that the Clarinet Concerto's slow movement stimulated feelings of love in me, you might as well say that I could get that feeling from Mahler's famous adagietto or any number of other works associated with feelings of tenderness. What makes my love for Mozart's compositions particular must be musical qualities; these clarify better why my sense of beauty is satisfied better by those compositions, irrespective of the impressions or emotions aroused by them.

>>114256480
Good classicals are handmade, and expensive. You won't find them on Sweetwater or Guitar center, and a budget concert level classical starts around $3k, and can go up to 10, 20k easily for the top luthiers. Pro players often have theirs custom made directly from the luthier, but some make guitars to be sold in stores. A classical is more akin to a por level violin than the mass produced guitars sold in retail.
It's a whole thing, veyr fart huffy and elitist, but they're insane quality. One of the top builders is
https://www.dominelliguitars.com/
It's $500 to just get on his waiting list, and sometimes he makes one or two a year he'll sell to the public. He doesn't list prices on his site. His guitars resell in the 5-7K range, used, and are highly sought after.

Most people shouldn't spend more than $300, though.

posts.com:
The premise that nobody gets this album is wrong. Anyonoe who read about how it was made totally gets it.

1) The two conventional tracks, Moonlight On Vermont and Veteran's Day Poppy, were recorded by his previous band two years prior. This was from the Strictly Personal sessions.

2) The music was composed by Beefheart on his piano, which he did not know how to play, and transcribed by Drumbo who taught it to the other musicians, who were almost all new to the Band.

3) They went into the studio and performed the music as transcribed.

4) Later, Zappa and Beefheart dubbed the vocals that Beefheart had written. But Beefheart wouldn't wear studio headphones so his vocals were dubbed out of sync half the time.

5) Zappa added some Mothers music to a couple of tracks, Old Fart At Play and The Blimp.


It sounds exactly like this is what happened, because htat is how it was cobbled together. Anyone doing this basic research can get how it sounds that way.

"Real Emo" only consists of the dc Emotional Hardcore scene and the late 90's Screamo scene. What is known by "Midwest Emo" is nothing but Alternative Rock with questionable real emo influence. When people try to argue that bands like My Chemical Romance are not real emo, while saying that Sunny Day Real Estate is, I can't help not to cringe because they are just as fake emo as My Chemical Romance (plus the pretentiousness). Real emo sounds ENERGETIC, POWERFUL and somewhat HATEFUL. Fake emo is weak, self pity and a failed attempt to direct energy and emotion into music. Some examples of REAL EMO are Pg 99, Rites of Spring, Cap n Jazz (the only real emo band from the midwest scene) and Loma Prieta. >>114244763
It's harder than it seems (and it does seem difficult) to get longer/progressive tracks to work in video games. They tend to be hilariously distracting and immersion-breaking whenever there is blatant mismatch with the action or, most insidiously, the lack thereof. At that point you have to design the game around the music rather than the other way around.
Moreover, the prog influence was already fizzling out by the time it was just barely feasible in terms of technical limitations and design repertoire to have a 10+ minute game event that remains interesting throughout.

>>114226168
I won't argue about superiority too much, but my personal favorite is no subgenre at all. For example, I don't think anything will ever make the genre look more glorious than the stuff Judas Priest did back in the day.
My next pick would probably be prog, because it simply can have so much potential by ignoring strict boundaries. I especially like how prog manages to fit intense musical sections together with more emotional and flowing parts. I don't think technical wankery has any value in prog though.
Other than that I think doom/sludge/drone trio also has much to offer, especially if you are one to appreciate acquired tastes. While black metal surely is nice, I think these three are better for two reasons- the weight of music just sticks so much better and these subgenres are just more focused on music itself and not relying on keeping a particular imagery. On the other hand, while I surely can also enjoy stoner doom, I agree it lacks creativity.

There's one thing I have strong opinion about, however: if a subgenre is not known for great live performances from bands, it's shit.

posts.com:
John Coltrane: A Love Supreme [Impulse, 1964]
This four-track, 33-minute January 1965 release is without question Coltrane's most beloved album. Only certified gold in 2001, it never cracked the Billboard 200 as it cemented 'Trane's divine status in Japan, was adored by American hippies from the Byrds and Carlos Santana on down, and served as theme music to Lester Bangs's wake at CBGB. The through-composed product of two weeks of solitary brainstorming at the Long Island home Coltrane had established with his new wife Alice, it's meditative rather than freewheeling, with each member of his classic quartet instructed to embark on his own harmonically mapped excursion and the title set to a chanted four-note melody you could hum in your sleep. I'm on my fourth consecutive play with no signs of tune fatigue as I write, plus my wife loves it. All true, all remarkable. But how much you value it, I expect, depends on how much faith you place in your own spirituality. Having finally freed my changer to move on to My Favorite Things, which I've loved since I bought it in 1960, I wonder how soon I'll play it again and regret to say that that may well depend on who dies when. And having purchased the Deluxe Edition CD to augment my vinyl, I say go for the single. A-

Rock'n'Roll is rhythmically-augmented Scotch Irish folk. Rock was blacks doing an impression of hillbilly music rather than hillbillies doing an impression of "black music". Even the supposed "blues notes" and tonalities come straight out of Scotch Irish music.(there is no blue note in West African music, meanwhile it has been a norm in the folk music of Great Britain for centuries)

Musicologists tend to ascribe some unique quality to African rhythm when it isn't there. The difference between African and Western music isn't in the rhythm, but in the focus on percussion. African music is tribal and meant to be accompanied by dance. Primitive music in all areas of the world started as highly percussive because that's what comes readily to us as human beings. Western music had centuries of development and went astray from those percussive roots long ago.

While Western music was exploring dissonance after entering the modern period, blacks in America started using Western theory and instruments to return to basic human impulse: the rhythm. Turning the focus towards percussion exploded in black music's popularity because Western art music became inaccessibly experimental and dissonant to general audiences. Jazz and Blues's percussive focus caught on hard because rhythm comes to us instinctively. The "We Waz Rawkers and shieet" myth is as solid as a bowel after eating too much Taco Bell.
